## Coding standards

- {{LANGUAGE_CONVENTIONS — e.g. "TypeScript strict; no `any`. Validate external
  input at the boundary with `{{VALIDATION_LIB}}`."}}
- **Small units.** Files {{e.g. 200–400 lines, 800 max}}; functions {{e.g. < 50
  lines}}. If it's bigger, it probably wants splitting.
- **Match the neighbors.** New code follows the conventions of the files around it
  — naming, structure, error handling, test style. Consistency beats personal
  preference.
- **Errors are handled, not swallowed.** No empty `catch`/`except` that hides a
  failure. Fail loudly or handle deliberately.
- {{ANY_PROJECT_SPECIFIC_PATTERNS — immutability, dependency rules, layering, etc.}}

## Change discipline

- **Delete the path you replace, in the same change.** No dead code, no
  commented-out blocks, no parallel old/new implementations behind a flag "just in
  case." Leave exactly one architecture behind. Conflicting parallel architectures
  are the #1 source of codebase rot.
- **Right-sized changes.** {{Your PR philosophy — e.g. "one PR per feature; split
  only on a true ordering dependency, never just because it's large."}}
- **No speculative abstraction.** Build for the requirements you have. Don't pay
  for flexibility you don't need yet.

## Verification (non-negotiable)

- **Verify before claiming done.** Run the actual build / tests / typecheck and
  read the output. Never report success you haven't observed. "It should work" is
  not "it works."
- {{GATE — e.g. "`{{TEST_CMD}}` and `{{TYPECHECK_CMD}}` must pass locally before
  you push. CI is a backstop, not the first check."}}
- For anything user-facing or money/data-path, prove it end-to-end the way a user
  would experience it — see `docs/testing-config.md`.

## Git & commits

- **Conventional commits with a required scope:** `<type>(<scope>): <description>`.
  Scope matches a feature/domain (`{{EXAMPLE_SCOPES}}`). {{Why it matters to you, if
  anything keys off it.}}
- **Session traceability (optional but recommended):** add a `Session-Id:` trailer
  so each commit links to the agent session that produced it:
  `git commit -m "..." --trailer "Session-Id: $CLAUDE_SESSION_ID"`. keel's session
  hooks set `$CLAUDE_SESSION_ID`; the `claude-sessions` skill uses the trailer to
  attribute commits to sessions.
- **Branch off fresh trunk.** `git fetch origin` then branch from `origin/{{DEFAULT_BRANCH}}`.
  A stale base is the most common cause of divergence. (The in-flight registry hook
  shows you how stale each branch is.)
- {{Confirm-before-outward-actions policy — pushing, opening PRs, deploying, etc.}}

## Parallel agents (if you run more than one)

- Before touching files, claim your scope: `tooling/workflow/workflow claim-scope
  '<glob>'`. It refuses if another live session already owns overlapping paths — so
  two agents never silently edit the same code.
- Heavy ops (tests, builds, installs) run under `with-heavy-lock` so parallel
  sessions queue instead of melting the machine. The `serialize-heavy-ops` hook
  enforces this.
- Worktrees live under {{`.worktrees/` or your convention}}; launch the agent from
  the main checkout, then `cd` into the worktree.

